{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>A pandemic is the worldwide spread of a new disease and occurs when a new virus emerges and spreads around the world, and most people do not have immunity. Viruses that have caused past pandemics typically originated from animal influenza viruses.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>The incubation period means the time between catching the virus and beginning to have symptoms of the disease. Most estimates of the incubation period for Covid 19 range from 1 to 14 days, most commonly around five days.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>In the event of a suspected case, special safety criteria are applied, which are recommended by the Ministry of Health in consultation with experts and specialists and derived from international guidelines. A sick person is isolated, contact persons are identified, informed and, depending on the situation, can be quarantined, for example. All measures aim to ensure that as few people as possible are infected by the pathogen.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>There isÂ notÂ enough epidemiological information at this time to determineÂ how easily andÂ sustainably this virus spreadsÂ between people, but it is currently estimated that, on average, one infected person will infect between two and three more.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>The virus that causes Covid 19 and the one that causes Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome are related to each other genetically, but they are different. {"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>On 31 December 2019, the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission in Wuhan City, Hubei province, China, reported a cluster of 27 pneumonia cases (including seven severe cases) of unknown aetiology, with a common reported link to Wuhan's Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market, a wholesale fish and live animal market. The market was closed down onÂ 1 January 2020. According to the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission, samples from the market tested positive for novel coronavirus. Cases showed symptoms such as fever, dry cough, dyspnoea; radiological findings showed bilateral lung infiltrates.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>In light of current knowledge, coronaviruses are not sexually transmitted. However, it is possible to transmit the coronavirus during sexual activity, especially if self-care measures to prevent virus transmission are not followed. Take care when giving kisses and with close facial contacts and avoid occasional sexual encounters or with people who are sick with respiratory symptoms.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>Population groups that have been more frequently reported having severe disease and death include people above 60 years of age, males, people with underlying conditions such as hypertension, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, chronic respiratory disease and cancer. The proportion of most of the reported chronic diseases and health conditions is similar to the prevalence of these conditions in the elderly age groups in China, therefore they might be surrogates of increasing age only. Higher ACE (angiotensin-converting enzyme II) gene expression may be linked to higher susceptibility to SARS CoV 2. It has been shown that ACE 2 expression in lung tissues increases with age, tobacco use and with some hypertensive treatment. These observations might explain the vulnerability of older people, tobacco users/smokers and those with hypertension; they also highlight the importance of identifying smokers as a potential vulnerable group for Covid 19.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>Preliminary findings indicate that the mortality rate for Covid 19 is twenty to thirty per thousand people diagnosed. This is significantly less than the 2003 SARS outbreak. However, it is much higher than the mortality rate for seasonal influenza.</speak>"}

{"type": "ssml","ssml": "<speak>It is too early to know how long the protective immune response against SARS CoV 2 will last, as this will require longitudinal serological studies that follow patientsâ€™ immunity over an extended period of time. Evidence from other coronavirus infections, like SARS and MERS, indicates that immunity may last for up to three years and re-infection with the same strain of seasonal circulating coronavirus is highly unlikely in the same or following season. This could also hold true for SARS CoV 2 as there is emerging evidence from early studies suggesting that individuals develop antibodies after infection and are likely to be immune from reinfection in the short term.</speak>"}
